  {
    "slide_type": "myth_fact",
    "bg_style": "dark",
    "theme": "editorial",
    "archetype": "thought_leader",
    "variant": "debunk",
    "params": {
      "myth": "Breakfast is universally recognized as the single most important meal of the day, and rigorous scientific consensus has established that anyone who skips breakfast will inevitably gain significant weight, suffer from decreased cognitive function throughout the morning hours, experience dangerously low blood sugar levels, and potentially develop long-term metabolic disorders that could have been entirely prevented by simply eating a balanced morning meal.",
      "fact": "Despite decades of conventional wisdom suggesting otherwise, a growing body of peer-reviewed research from institutions including the University of Bath, Cornell University, and the British Journal of Nutrition has consistently found no significant correlation between breakfast consumption and weight management, cognitive performance, or metabolic health in adults \u2014 with some studies even suggesting that intermittent fasting patterns including breakfast skipping may offer certain health benefits.",
      "explanation": "The widespread belief in breakfast's supreme importance can be traced back to aggressive marketing campaigns by cereal manufacturers in the early-to-mid twentieth century, particularly James Caleb Jackson and John Harvey Kellogg, who had both financial and ideological motivations to promote regular grain consumption as essential to human health."
    }
  },
